A.1 Proof of Theorem 2.1 (Discrete Contraction with ISS)

Theorem 2.1 (Incremental Exponential Convergence with ISS).
Let \Phi: \mathcal{S} \times \mathcal{D} \to \mathcal{S} be a discrete-time map and assume there exists a Finsler metric F such that for all s,s' \in \mathcal{S} and disturbances d,d'

F(\Phi(s,d),\Phi(s',d')) \le \alpha F(s,s') + \gamma(\|d-d'\|)
\]  

with \alpha \in (0,1) and \gamma \in \mathcal{K}. Then for any two trajectories s_k,s'_k with \|d_k-d'_k\| \le \bar{d},

F(s_k,s'_k) \le \alpha^k F(s_0,s'_0) + \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}.

Proof. We proceed by induction. For k=0 the inequality is trivial. Assume it holds at step k. Then

F(s_{k+1},s'_{k+1}) \le \alpha F(s_k,s'_k) + \gamma(\|d_k-d'_k\|).
\]  

By the induction hypothesis,

\alpha F(s_k,s'_k) \le \alpha^{k+1} F(s_0,s'_0) + \alpha \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}.
\]  

Since \gamma(\|d_k-d'_k\|) \le \gamma(2\bar{d}) (because \gamma is increasing), we obtain

F(s_{k+1},s'_{k+1}) \le \alpha^{k+1} F(s_0,s'_0) + \left(\alpha \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha} + \gamma(2\bar{d})\right) = \alpha^{k+1} F(s_0,s'_0) + \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}.
\]  

Thus the inequality holds for all k. The convergence to a ball of radius \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha} follows by letting k \to \infty. ∎

