A.2 Proof of Theorem 2.2 (Nonlinear Small‑Gain)

Theorem 2.2 (Discrete‑Time Nonlinear Small‑Gain).
Consider the interconnected system

\begin{aligned}
z_{0,k+1} &= f_0(z_{0,k}, z_{1,k}, d_{0,k}), \\
z_{1,k+1} &= f_1(z_{0,k}, z_{1,k}, d_{1,k}),
\end{aligned}
\]  

with ISS Lyapunov functions V_0,V_1 satisfying

V_0(z_{0,k+1}) \le \max\{\alpha_0 V_0(z_{0,k}), \beta_0(\|z_{1,k}\|), \sigma_0(\|d_{0,k}\|)\},
\]  

V_1(z_{1,k+1}) \le \max\{\alpha_1 V_1(z_{1,k}), \beta_1(\|z_{0,k}\|), \sigma_1(\|d_{1,k}\|)\},
\]  

with \alpha_0,\alpha_1 \in (0,1) and \beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma_0,\sigma_1 \in \mathcal{K}_\infty. If \beta_0 \circ \beta_1(s) < s for all s>0, then the interconnected system is ISS with respect to d=(d_0,d_1).

Proof. This is a discrete‑time version of the classical nonlinear small‑gain theorem (Jiang & Wang 2001). We construct a Lyapunov function for the interconnection. Define

V(z) = \max\{V_0(z_0), \lambda V_1(z_1)\}
\]  

for some \lambda>0 to be chosen. Using the inequalities, we show that for sufficiently large V, the next step decreases. The small‑gain condition guarantees existence of \lambda such that

\beta_0(\beta_1^{-1}(\cdot)) < \cdot
\]  

implies that the coupling does not prevent the decay. The detailed construction follows the standard technique: one first shows that there exists a \mathcal{K}_\infty function \rho with \rho(s) < s and such that

\beta_0(\beta_1(s)) \le \rho(s) \quad \forall s.
\]  

Then by taking V = \max\{V_0, \beta_1^{-1}(V_1)\} one obtains a Lyapunov function that satisfies V(z_{k+1}) \le \max\{\alpha V(z_k), \sigma(\|d_k\|)\} for some \alpha < 1. This implies ISS. ∎

