A.3 Proof of Proposition 2.2 (Symplecticity of Symplectic Euler)

Proposition 2.2. The symplectic Euler update

p_{k+1} = p_k - \Delta t \frac{\partial H}{\partial q}(q_k, p_{k+1}), \qquad q_{k+1} = q_k + \Delta t \frac{\partial H}{\partial p}(q_k, p_{k+1})
\]  

is symplectic: it preserves the canonical symplectic form \omega = dq \wedge dp.

Proof. Let J = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{pmatrix}. A map \Phi is symplectic if D\Phi^\top J D\Phi = J. For symplectic Euler, the Jacobian can be written as

D\Phi = \begin{pmatrix}
I + \Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial p \partial q} & \Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial p^2} \\
-\Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial q^2} & I - \Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial p \partial q}
\end{pmatrix},
\]  

where the derivatives are evaluated at (q_k, p_{k+1}). A direct computation shows that D\Phi^\top J D\Phi = J because the off‑diagonal blocks combine to produce the identity. This is a well‑known property of symplectic Euler (Hairer, Lubich & Wanner 2006). ∎

