Appendix B: Mathematical Background

B.1 Finsler Manifolds and Krasovskii Lyapunov Functions

A Finsler manifold is a differentiable manifold \mathcal{S} together with a function F: T\mathcal{S} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} that is positively homogeneous and convex in the tangent direction, and smooth away from the zero section. Finsler metrics generalize Riemannian metrics and are well‑suited for spaces where the geometry is not quadratic (e.g., due to discrete modes). For a discrete‑time system, a Krasovskii‑type Lyapunov function is a function that satisfies the inequality V(\Phi(s,d)) \le \lambda V(s) + \sigma(\|d\|). Such functions are known to characterize ISS for discrete systems (Jiang & Wang 2001). The combination of Finsler metrics with Krasovskii‑type Lyapunov functions allows handling of non‑smooth dynamics and categorical states by embedding them into a continuous space with a barrier function.

B.2 Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS) and Discrete‑Time ISS

A system x_{k+1} = f(x_k, u_k) is input‑to‑state stable if there exist \beta \in \mathcal{KL} and \gamma \in \mathcal{K} such that for any initial state and any bounded input sequence u_k,

\|x_k\| \le \beta(\|x_0\|, k) + \gamma(\sup_{0 \le i \le k-1} \|u_i\|).
\]  

For discrete‑time systems, a Lyapunov characterization exists: there exists a function V such that

V(x_{k+1}) \le \lambda V(x_k) + \sigma(\|u_k\|)
\]  

with \lambda \in (0,1) and \sigma \in \mathcal{K}_\infty (or more general functions). This is the form we use.

B.3 Symplectic Geometry and Variational Integrators

A symplectic manifold is a manifold equipped with a closed, non‑degenerate 2‑form \omega. The canonical example is \mathbb{R}^{2n} with \omega = \sum_i dq_i \wedge dp_i. A map \Phi is symplectic if \Phi^*\omega = \omega. Symplectic integrators are numerical methods that preserve the symplectic structure exactly. The symplectic Euler method is a first‑order symplectic integrator. For Hamiltonian systems with separable Hamiltonians H(q,p) = T(p) + V(q), symplectic Euler is often written as

p_{k+1} = p_k - \Delta t V'(q_k), \quad q_{k+1} = q_k + \Delta t T'(p_{k+1}),
\]  

which is the form we use. This method is known to have excellent long‑term energy stability (Hairer, Lubich & Wanner 2006).

B.4 Sum‑of‑Squares Programming and Polynomial Optimization

A polynomial p(x) is a sum‑of‑squares (SOS) if it can be written as p(x) = \sum_i q_i(x)^2 for some polynomials q_i. SOS polynomials are obviously non‑negative. The set of SOS polynomials of a given degree is characterized by a semidefinite program (SDP). Sum‑of‑squares programming is a powerful tool for finding polynomial Lyapunov functions and verifying polynomial inequalities over semi‑algebraic sets. The SOS condition is sufficient for the inequality to hold globally, and can be used to enforce positivity of the contraction LMI. For polynomial systems, this approach yields rigorous, computationally verifiable certificates.

B.5 Martingale Theory and Azuma‑Hoeffding Inequality

A stochastic process \{M_k\} is a martingale with respect to a filtration \{\mathcal{F}_k\} if \mathbb{E}[M_{k+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_k] = M_k. A supermartingale satisfies \mathbb{E}[M_{k+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \le M_k. The Azuma–Hoeffding inequality states that if \{X_k\} is a martingale difference sequence with |X_k| \le c_k almost surely, then for any \epsilon > 0,

\mathbb{P}\left( \left| \sum_{i=1}^n X_i \right| \ge \epsilon \right) \le 2 \exp\left( -\frac{\epsilon^2}{2\sum_{i=1}^n c_i^2} \right).
\]  

This inequality is used to bound the probability of large deviations of a supermartingale, which we apply to the Lyapunov function deviation.

