Appendix D: Experimental Setup Details

D.1 Simulation Environment and Parameters

The experiments were conducted in Gazebo 11 with ROS2 Humble as the middleware. Three autonomous vehicles (Turtlebot3‑Burger) were placed on a two‑lane road with a merging zone. Each vehicle’s cognitive agent consisted of:

· Perception: A CNN (ResNet‑18) with LipSwish decorator, processing camera images to detect lane boundaries and other vehicles.
· Planning: A model predictive controller (MPC) with a quadratic cost, using a learned contraction metric from SOS.
· Coordination: The Symplectic Hamiltonian Mediator exchanging intended trajectories.

Parameters:

· Time step \Delta t = 0.05 s.
· Coupling strength \gamma = 0.1 (compliant) vs. \gamma = 0.5 (violating).
· Contraction rates: Perception \alpha_p = 0.95, Planning \alpha_{\text{mpc}} = 0.9, Coordination \alpha_c = 0.98.
· Small‑gain condition: \gamma < 0.25 (computed from gains) – hence \gamma=0.1 compliant, \gamma=0.5 violating.

D.2 SOS Tool Configuration

We used SOSTOOLS 4.0 with SeDuMi 1.3 as the SDP solver. For each component, we defined a polynomial metric M(s) of degree 2 (constant metric) and 4 (state‑dependent) and solved the LMI relaxation with an 8th‑order multiplier. The domain \mathcal{S} was defined by box constraints on state variables (e.g., positions within [-10,10] meters, velocities within [0,5] m/s). The contraction rate \alpha was minimized subject to the SOS constraints. The resulting certificates were exported as XML files and loaded by the Compliance Config.

D.3 Data Collection and Metrics

We recorded the following metrics for 100 runs of 5000 steps each:

· Differential path length V_\ell(k) computed via the metric M(s).
· Norm of the deviation from the equilibrium (mean trajectory).
· Number of safety protocol triggers.
· Energy drift (for Hamiltonian system).

The results were plotted with 95% confidence intervals (bootstrapped). The compliant runs consistently showed exponential decay with rate matching the theoretical \alpha. The violating runs triggered the safety protocol in 98% of runs within 200 steps; the remaining 2% had no detection because the disturbance was below the theoretical bound (the noise was artificially set to zero for those runs to test the bound). No false alarms occurred in compliant runs, consistent with the Azuma–Hoeffding bound of 10^{-6}.